title: NBA 2K25 =My Career= [PC] (4K) EP343 {Playoffs: West Semis} Game 4 {Thunder @ Nuggets}
content: NBA 2K25 is a video game that is part of the NBA 2K series. The game is set to be released for Nintendo Switch, PlayStation 4, PlayStation 5, Windows, Xbox One and Xbox Series X/S on September 6, 2024, and early access became available on September 4, 2024. The game was announced on July 10, 2024 and is the first instance in the NBA 2K series that features cover art with both NBA and WNBA players on the same release, with the All-Star Edition featuring Jayson Tatum of the Boston Celtics and A'ja Wilson of the Las Vegas Aces. The Standard Edition has Tatum, WNBA Edition has Wilson, and the Naismith Hall of Fame Edition features Vince Carter, who led a crop of inductees scheduled to enter the month after this game was released. This will be the first installment of the series where the PC edition will have all of the features of the home console editions, minus cross-play support and anti-cheat, which is only on PlayStation 5 and Xbox Series X/S.[3] NBA 2K25 has ProPlay, a technology introduced in the predecessor NBA 2K24, which turns real NBA footage into animations in-game for players. Using ProPlay, 9,000 new animations are added. The game additionally features a new dribble engine and a new defensive movement system. NBA 2K25 introduces Legend Badges and additional attributes beyond your builds cap. In MyCareer, stamina has been removed from the builder and is now earned through working out at a Gatorade facility. Also, the acceleration rating has been replaced with agility. The badge regression introduced in NBA 2K24 has been removed. Command every court with authenticity and realism Powered by ProPLAY‚Ñ¢, giving you ultimate control over how you play in NBA 2K25. content: I'm 42 and I am better with my eating than I used to be. I did the same thing when I was about to same age. When I was very young, I ate basically everything. Chicken on the bone, just about every vegetable, I've never been much for fruit. Apples, watermelon and grapes were about it. Then when I was around 3 or 4, I stopped eating all together. The only thing that went in my mouth was the kid's Flintstones chewable vitamins and lemon lime Gatorade. I don't remember how long that went on or any of my weight statistics. I just started eating again at some point. I'm not sure if my food aversions started right after that or some time later.  I wish I had a dollar for every time I heard, she will eat if she's hungry enough. I promise you I literally will not. The people that have attempted to force me to eat. I know when I was older, 8 or 9 and up there was a lot of trauma around eating but that's not appropriate to talk about here.  All of that to say, I am so proud of Toren for stepping out of his comfort zone to try things. He has inspired me to try a few new things and some I have genuinely liked! Some others were disgusting. But I gave each a good try! ‚ù§

content: In South Korea, Eolbaksa, a portmanteau of ice, Bacchus, and Chilsung CIDER, is more than a drink‚Äîit‚Äôs a cultural lifeline. This homemade concoction, born in jjimjilbangs, blends caffeine, electrolytes, and vitamins for a quick reprieve from chronic fatigue. Gamers and students, running on empty, mix variants like Power-Bak-Gal-Bae, combining Bacchus, pear juice, and Powerade, or Eolpobi, with Pocari Sweat and Vita 500. These ‚Äúboong-boong drinks‚Äù emerged in the 2000s when commercial energy drinks were scarce, offering a mental lift for exam-cramming youth. YouTube tutorials like ‚ÄúPharmacist‚Äôs Secret Anti-Fatigue Drink‚Äù go viral, but experts warn of risks. ‚ÄúIt‚Äôs risky to assume a drink is safe just because someone says it works,‚Äù says Kang Jae-heon, noting potential sugar or caffeine overload. Sim Kyung-won adds that such mixes may irritate digestion or cause palpitations. Sociology professor Koo Jeong-woo links their rise to relentless competition, painting a generation desperate to stay awake and ahead, fueled by these inventive, yet risky, energy blends.

content: Trump‚Äôs Amateur Hour: A Gold Medal Distraction from Epstein and a Love Letter to the ‚Äô50s Donald Trump‚Äôs latest political sideshow‚Äîa toothless executive order on amateur sports‚Äîisn‚Äôt about saving college athletes from capitalism. It‚Äôs about saving himself from scrutiny. Specifically, the kind of scrutiny that comes when your name appears in the Jeffrey Epstein files, your Speaker of the House is in hiding, and your entire movement looks like a game of musical chairs played on a trapdoor. The executive order is vintage Trump. It waves a flag, makes noise, and changes nothing. It postures about "saving amateurism" in college sports, about protecting women‚Äôs rowing teams and Olympic dreamers, while ignoring the reality: the amateur model is already dead, gutted by courts, cracked open by state law, and abandoned by a generation of athletes who got tired of being free labor for bloated university athletic departments. But Trump doesn‚Äôt care about facts. He cares about headlines. And if the headlines aren‚Äôt about him doing something ‚Äúpresidential,‚Äù they‚Äôre about him throwing parties for "calendar girls" with Epstein as the only other guest. So we get a made-for-Fox-News moment where Trump‚Äîwho thinks driving a golf cart qualifies as athletic performance‚Äîpretends to defend the purity of college sports. The same man who once bragged about being the best baseball player in New York but has trouble walking down a ramp. Let‚Äôs be honest: Trump‚Äôs relationship to sports is purely performative. He tried to buy the Buffalo Bills. He tried to make the USFL compete with the NFL. He failed at both. He reportedly cheats at golf like it‚Äôs a bodily reflex. He lives for the photo ops with helmets and jerseys, the sidelines at Alabama-LSU, the cheers that feel like validation. He isn‚Äôt a sportsman‚Äîhe‚Äôs a fanboy with executive power and a score to settle. So now he wants to ‚Äúsave‚Äù amateurism? From what? From progress? From equity? From athletes realizing they have value beyond a free meal plan and a torn ACL? Trump‚Äôs executive order tries to freeze-frame the system back to the Eisenhower era, when athletes shut up, played for free, and hoped a booster handed them a handshake full of twenties. He invokes Title IX like a shield, as if suddenly he‚Äôs the champion of women‚Äôs sports. But this isn‚Äôt about gender equity. It‚Äôs about political optics. It‚Äôs about pointing to the chaos in college athletics and pretending you‚Äôre the adult in the room while the walls are on fire. And here‚Äôs the kicker: it‚Äôs all bark, no bite. Executive orders don‚Äôt rewrite court decisions. They don‚Äôt erase state laws. They don‚Äôt reverse the NIL tsunami. What they do is redirect federal grants, send memos to agencies, and give Fox News something to shout about for 48 hours. It‚Äôs symbolism soaked in nostalgia. It‚Äôs an op-ed written in Sharpie and masquerading as governance. Meanwhile, real questions go unanswered. Why did Trump shut down the House early when the Epstein files dropped? Why does the Justice Department seem allergic to transparency? Why are victims still waiting for accountability? These are not questions Trump wants trending. So he does what he always does: he manufactures a crisis to bury a scandal. He puts on the red hat, waves a flag, and barks about tradition while dragging the country deeper into dysfunction. Trump‚Äôs amateur sports order isn‚Äôt policy. It‚Äôs performance art. It‚Äôs a dog whistle to the college football dads in MAGA hats who think the real threat to America isn‚Äôt corruption or child abuse cover-ups‚Äîit‚Äôs a 19-year-old quarterback making money off a Gatorade ad. It‚Äôs another act in the farce, another distraction from the truth, another round of make-believe from a man whose only real sport is evasion. So let‚Äôs call it what it is: a gold-plated golf cart stunt. An executive order for the cameras, not the courts. A swing and a miss from a man who never learned how to play the game but insists on being in every highlight reel. And while the cameras pan away to cover Trump‚Äôs pretend crusade to protect college sports, the real rot‚Äîthe names, the documents, the secrets‚Äîsits just below the surface, waiting for someone brave enough to stop pretending.
